## Rule Categories

Rules in `.cursor/rules/` are applied automatically.

### 1. AI-Assisted Development (.cursor/rules/ai-assisted-development.mdc)
- Plan before coding; implement in small, reviewable steps
- Validate structure first for new features (skeleton then logic)
- Re-plan when something feels off; donâ€™t refactor legacy out of scope
- Review checklist: layer, naming, i18n, no hardcoded values, types, a11y

### 2. Code Quality (.cursor/rules/code-quality.mdc)
- Clean code standards
- Error handling
- Security best practices
- Performance considerations
- Code complexity management
- Testing requirements

### 3. Documentation (.cursor/rules/documentation.mdc)
- Code documentation standards
- README requirements
- API documentation
- Architecture documentation
- Inline comments guidelines

### 4. Naming Conventions (.cursor/rules/naming-conventions.mdc)
- Variable and function naming
- Class and type naming
- File and directory naming
- Language-specific conventions
- Database and API naming

### 5. TypeScript Patterns (.cursor/rules/typescript-patterns.mdc)
- Type safety: avoid `any`, use `unknown` and type guards; strict mode; interface vs type
- Discriminated unions for complex state
- Utility types: Partial, Pick, Omit, Record, ReturnType, etc.
- Generics: constraints, default params, avoid over-engineering
- Advanced: `as const`, `satisfies`, readonly, template literal types

### 6. Modern JS/TS Patterns (.cursor/rules/modern-js-ts-patterns.mdc)
- Async/await over promise chains; Promise.all / allSettled; no async in forEach
- Optional chaining (`?.`) and nullish coalescing (`??`)
- Destructuring for params and defaults; map/filter/reduce, some/every, find/findIndex

## Core Principles

### Code Quality
- Write self-documenting code
- Keep functions small and focused (20-30 lines ideal)
- Handle errors explicitly
- Validate all inputs
- Follow security best practices
- Maintain low complexity
- Write comprehensive tests

### Documentation
- Document all public APIs
- Keep README files comprehensive and up-to-date
- Use appropriate documentation tools
- Include code examples
- Maintain changelogs

### Naming
- Use descriptive names that reveal intent
- Follow language-specific conventions
- Be consistent throughout the codebase
- Avoid abbreviations and generic names
- Use appropriate prefixes for booleans

## Language-Specific Guidelines

### JavaScript/TypeScript
- Use `const` over `let`, avoid `var`
- Use `===` instead of `==`
- Prefer async/await over promise chains
- Use arrow functions for callbacks
- Follow camelCase for variables/functions
- Use PascalCase for classes/interfaces

### Python
- Follow PEP 8 style guide
- Use snake_case for variables/functions
- Use PascalCase for classes
- Use type hints where applicable
- Follow the Zen of Python

### Java
- Follow Java naming conventions
- Use camelCase for variables/methods
- Use PascalCase for classes
- Handle checked exceptions appropriately
- Prefer composition over inheritance

### Go
- Follow Go naming conventions
- Handle all errors explicitly
- Use interfaces for abstraction
- Keep functions small and focused
- Export only what's necessary

